The menu of a fat-addicted child: It does not breakfast and eats for the evening bread sausage
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Current surveys have shown - obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
Again, it shows how important the environment in which a person grows up and the examples that surround him is for the healthy development of a person.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half as often on the table as in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had potatoes for dinner on the day before the enlightenment campaign under the motto “Obesity is not a coincidence.”
In families with small children, sport is also not exactly one of the favorite occupations, however, which also affects the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second anniversary of the “Adipositas is not a coincidence” campaign, which is supported by the General Hospital and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the horrific increase in the number of overweight or even obese children.
“For example, only half of the children surveyed led, five times a day, to eat breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper dinner — one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” said one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative little things, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are important for a child’s healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of students’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
The worst was the finding that in every tenth family is not breakfasted at all.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that in the families of overweight children, unhealthy potatoes are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do – only 15 percent.
Set up your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compose their own meal plan from offered options according to appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming above all is the great popularity of sweet lemonade," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, doughnuts won close to poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
The Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of the respondents, who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the informative lecture "Adipositas is not a coincidence", there was in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of a healthy diet," the results of the project stated.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give preference to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed poultry or fish much more often than the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less noodles or sweet foods.
