IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to World Wings
Founded a hundred years ago in New York City, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name – Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous plug-in card clocks for registering the beginning and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who had also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shadows - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and selling all sorts of machines for trading – from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash registers.
In the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled its revenue to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM engineers and computers helped guide NASA's flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous man's flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard at the time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consulting stake of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off in the last three years is the concept of “Smart Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and in urban administration.
In the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform, which is designed to help retailers lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia – the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe headquarters is based in Prague and is home to a world-class research team that deals with voice recognition technology.
