Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the Czech Republic: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at the time mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West at the time only selected ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia embarked on a prowestern course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter to do so, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or also stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good friends" in the travel agency.
That was not the case for a long time.
The so-called currency statement - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a currency statement it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the country, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and Datchens - a habit that continues to this day.
The simultaneous revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of then Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply couldn’t get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
For example, when travelling to Paris, the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park, because who had already had the money for accommodation in a hotel or a guesthouse at the time.
A typical feature of Czech travel abroad was a full-packed suitcase with canned beer, permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech krone - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, average wages increased, which in 1997 marked another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare travel through charter flights after 1997, making flight travel incredibly affordable, thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts, compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had currency-free payment traffic with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-common" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly to far-off sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations fly directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most highly developed countries in the world.
For the first time in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 per capita on a single holiday stay including the cost at the resort.
