Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time in front of his computer attack and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists supporting far-right groups on social media.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It’s easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s concealment of personal data is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — as marketers have done for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans from far-right groups across Europe and then visualized them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or a new dietary product, the adds invited users to a survey in which their educational status, their own attitude towards violence, and their own assessments were assessed.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new method of research,” says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online advocates of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more rational, democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as “likes”, text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook’s “Data Supernova” is generating a research tree that has increased the number of scientific work titled this page by almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this site people that you don’t usually reach with your clipboard on the street.
“If you tried to interview people of the British National Party earlier, it was very difficult to identify them.”
"They had to inform the party first, and they would never have allowed them access," Bartlett says.
“It’s all gone on Facebook – you’re going straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full noise on Facebook were significantly more likely to drink problems than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that equal students, such as housing consultants, monitor the page and help a student if they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
“We have found a way to identify endangered children who would otherwise not have been found.”
Facebook is also constantly collecting the data of its own population.
The data team of the site has created statistics about the relationship status and Valentine’s Day, election participation in the mid-term elections 2010 and a national luck index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to - masters of digital freedoms for a long time to know that the site should make its big data gains for other pits).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to provide its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know anything about yet?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have thought at all about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, in a 2006 study in which he surveyed the public pages of students on Facebook.
“As far as she was concerned, it was only about her and her friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information is true in a user profile and in posts.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” says Selwyn.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research needs to take care of social – and every lot of social life is still taking place offline.”
