The quintet included Costa Rica on its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive conversation with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament says the band is ready to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
More than 20 years they have been expected, but the band assures them that a dream will come true when they play in Costa Rica.
The group’s bassist and co-founder, Jeff Ament, assured Viva of an exclusive interview last week from Brazil.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the interview, the full copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been on vacation in Costa Rica once. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It’s exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely surrendered and they experience the days before the concert more intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we're sorry for taking so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn't that a little pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on a couple of huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we like to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and are fascinated by the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends have always been surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, the excellent surfing area. In this way, about people who love surfing, we learned about it.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t set any limits.
We will try to give the best show possible with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You will never repeat your repertoire.
- Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes a different song, so the decision we’re each going to play isn’t easy.
If we record two or three songs that we haven’t played for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they might be forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think that’s why it’s also for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your 20-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us have imagined playing in a great rock band once, even for over 20 years.
We continue to rely on these blessings and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like it and are excited about making music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be any better.
What did it mean for you to have been actively involved in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are well friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Time and again a band emerges from a city, but it is already unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and proud to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are excited to still be friends with them all and we are honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago, which alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we all appreciate the happiness of being still alive and, moreover, we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One's familiar with the other and his music, and we couldn't be better off.
Your relationship with glory has not always been easy; on the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it’s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought into being, without being a famous rock star, which has never interested us anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was great in the beginning.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed about what it took so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what kind of an incredible person Andy was about and how he always made me laugh.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their works, especially Eddie Vedder, and therefore have chosen the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the best. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas live has to offer. That's definitely going to be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
This is a question for Eddie Vedder, I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that happens to him.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
So many <0x2B>
The first ones I like include Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it was no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I think we all don't feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think about the bands I mentioned earlier, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney make better than ever.
At first, her music was darker, now she is more positive.
- Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little lightweight, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in themselves.
Both of them came to me with tears when I heard Ed play them. They're very dark songs.
I believe that as you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life – for example, if you lose a family member or a friend – that influences your artistic creation and your music and these two songs embodies that clearly for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
