Asphalt from UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the number of signs that come from the road surface were taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 impact holes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico) were to break out, he said.
In his lecture on "Technical Holes", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory, for which he is responsible, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, which, however, never has a greater mechanical resistance at such a temperature.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believed that this type of modified asphalt in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, should be used to improve the behavior of road surfaces and thus avoid the occurrence of impact holes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthens.
The asphalt's elasticity means that at high temperatures of almost 180<0xC2><0xB0> C. it behaves like a liquid, at 120<0xC2><0xB0> C. it is very tensile and at 50<0xC2><0xB0> C. it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in a day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible road covering, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the top layers is a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer, had been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles continue to move on and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," the chemical engineer said.
“Over the wear layer,” he said, “a last layer will be laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
The road surface receives and distributes most of the forces, the support layer also needs a suitable thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
Weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water,” he said, “because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets wet, water penetrates into the layer and only hardly exits. This causes a softening of all the layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of impact holes.
If a punch hole is created, he said, "the cover layer will first be worn off, while the wear layer will only be impaired afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the appearance of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in proportion to the recessed load of the vehicle, and it must be safe to say that it is in proportion to the recessed load of the vehicle.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the impact holes could be repaired easily and without using high temperatures.
